    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Chinese Threats And a Missile Shield</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Frank Lechner letter says warning from China's chief arms negotiator that China would respond with buildup of nuclear weapons to United States development of missile shield (May 11 article) shows that China is geopolitical adversary aspiring to superpower status</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>China's chief arms negotiator warns that if the United States develops a missile defense shield, his country will respond with an arms buildup to ''defeat your system'' and thereby preserve a ''balance of terror'' (front page, May 11).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>China's chief arms negotiator warns that if the United States develops a missile defense shield, his country will respond with an arms buildup to ''defeat your system'' and thereby preserve a ''balance of terror'' (front page, May 11).</p>
        <p>Such comments indicate that China is not America's ''strategic partner.'' Instead, it is a geopolitical adversary aspiring to superpower status. Its threat adds justification to development of a missile shield. Its position further suggests that China's entry into the World Trade Organization, whatever its economic merits may be, is unlikely to assuage its government's hostility to key United States interests.</p>
        <p>FRANK LECHNER  Atlanta, May 11, 2000</p>
      </block>
